If $X$ is $T_3$, it is $T_2$.  So given distinct points $a,b\in X$, there are disjoint open $O_a$ and $O_b$ containing $a$ and $b$ respectively. Then $a \notin \operatorname{cl}(O_b)$ and by regularity there is an open $U$ containing $a$ with $\operatorname{cl}(U) \cap \operatorname{cl}(O_b) = \emptyset$.

Asserted in Figure 1 of {{doi:10.1007/978-1-4612-6290-9}}
(where T_3 means regular).

If $f:X \rightarrow [0,1]$ is a continuous function with $f(a)=0$ and $f(B)=\{1\}$, then $f^{-1}([0,\frac{1}{3}))$ and $f^{-1}((\frac{2}{3},1])$ are disjoint open sets with disjoint closures containing $a$ and $B$ respectively.

Asserted in Figure 1 of {{doi:10.1007/978-1-4612-6290-9}}
(where T_3 means regular and T_{3.5} means completely regular).

As defined on page 223 of {{doi:10.1007/978-1-4612-6290-9}}
all continuous functions from a hyperconnected space to the
reals are constant.

As defined on page 223 of {{doi:10.1007/978-1-4612-6290-9}}
all continuous functions from a strongly connected space to the
reals are constant and thus have compact images.

Follows from the definition on page 31 of {{doi:10.1007/978-1-4612-6290-9}}
as the path connecting two distinct points would yield a nonsingleton path
component.

By the main theorem of the article {{doi:10.1090/S0002-9939-1973-0322812-9}},
if $X$ is {P7}, embeds as a closed subspace of product of {P194} spaces (e.g. it is itself {P194}),
and every closed discrete subspace of $X$ is {P164} (e.g. it is itself {P164}), then $X$ is {P162}.

The $\Sigma$-product

$\quad Y=\{x=(x_\alpha)\in\mathbb R^\Gamma:\{\alpha:x_\alpha\ne 0\}\text{ is countable}\}$

for some set $\Gamma$ is a subgroup of the topological group $(\mathbb R^\Gamma,+)$
with the product topology, and is {P187}
since {S25|P187}
and the {P187} property is preserved by $\Sigma$-products.

Assuming $X$ is nonempty, let $x$ be a point of $X$.  By {P24},
$x$ has an open neighborhood $V$ with compact closure.  But in a {P39}
space every nonempty open set is dense.  So $X=\overline V$ is compact.

See Theorem 2.3 in {{zb:0555.54015}}.

The proof shows that if $X$ satisfies the hypotheses, it is {P110}.
The rest follows by results known to pi-base:
{P133} spaces are {P88}
[(Explore)](https://topology.pi-base.org/spaces?q=LOTS%2B%7ECollectionwise+normal)
and {P1};
hence $X$ is {P53}
[(Explore)](https://topology.pi-base.org/spaces?q=Collectionwise+normal%2BDevelopable%2B%24T_0%24%2B%7EMetrizable).

This is Corollary 3 of {{zb:0164.53101}}
([ResearchGate](https://www.researchgate.net/publication/248119266_Total_paracompactness_and_paracompact_dispersed_spaces)),
where "paracompact" assumes {P3}
and "dispersed" means {P51}.
